Berlin Black Book

Culty department stores and an edgy arts scene, experimental cuisine and cosy, classic schnitzel spots...we’re finally ready to tackle this huge and slightly intimidating city.

I’m always a little embarrassed when someone asks me about the last time I’ve been to a certain place and I have to say it’s been years, or never. It’s not that I don’t have the interest; I just find it’s easier to be a return traveler to places I’m deeply connected to, and when I want to experience a new place, I want to be armed with intel from people I trust. (Hopefully we are that for you now!) 

Of course, I’ve always wanted to visit Berlin, but somehow never put it on the calendar because I hadn’t managed to pull together all the necessary research. But in the last year, I’ve found myself in touch with more than a few locals and friends who know the city well, and I made a point of asking them for their lists. Not that anyone needs convincing to visit this incredible cultural capital that always feels like the center of cool. But if, like, me, you’ve never been (or it’s been a while), I think this description from Gisela Williams and Antje Wewer—Berlin-based magazine veterans who recently launched the w-report, a travel and culture-focused Substack, and who contributed to our list below—sells it is so well: “We love Berlin because it’s still a city flush with creative possibilities, sown with unexpected and experimental projects and places. It’s populated by countless world class contemporary artists and designers, from Hella Jongerius to Olafur Eliasson and Danh Vo. But…often these projects are hidden and difficult to find. Berlin is not easy to navigate, especially for first timers. Partly because it’s huge, nine times the size of Paris; every neighborhood is its own universe. Also because if you’ve ever stood in line in Berghain, the city’s most legendary nightclub, you know that whatever passes for cool in other cities—Instagramming the hell out of something, wearing head-to-toe designer, flashing cash—does not cut it in Berlin.” ​ 

So now I’m ready to go, and I hope we can compare notes soon! —Y.E.

OUR CONTRIBUTORS

Alex Eagle is a dear friend who lives in London, and is also the creative director of The Store X Berlin at the Soho House Berlin.

Claudio Kühn is a Yolo subscriber and Berliner who shared a long list of recs with us; he runs his own law firm in the city, where he relocated 12 years ago after living in Munich, Lausanne, Istanbul and Shanghai.

Eugenia Gonzalez is a Berlin-based freelance writer for Vogue México & Latinoamérica, who contributed to Condé Nast Traveler when we were there and last wrote about Marseille for Yolo.

Gisela Williams and Antje Wewer are Berlin-based travel and culture writers behind the new Substack, w-report. We’ve followed Gisela’s scoops for years as a contributing editor to T Magazine and Travel & Leisure; Antje Wewer (“the other W”) is an editor at Salon.

Meike Peters is a James Beard award-winning cookbook author based in Berlin, who has just come out with the brilliant cookbook, Noon. 

Nina Knaudt is one half of Rianna + Nina, a Berlin-based brand who make the most beautiful dresses, but also incredible accessories and coats. 

Rachel Coleman is a social media consultant based in Berlin. Before moving there five years ago, she lived in NYC and worked on the social media team at Condé Nast Traveler with us! 

Robert Kittel is the Munich-based founder of Pretty Hotels, a site we always turn to for small, unique and design-centric stays.

Stephanie Hering is the founder and designer of Hering Berlin, who manufacture the most elegant porcelain and glass tableware. 

Tina Lutz is the founder and designer of Lutz Morris, a line of luxury leather goods handmade consciously in Germany. She’s also a dear friend who has been after me to visit this great city for ages.

HOTELS + STAYS

My three favorites are Hotel Wilmina in Berlin-Charlottenburg, a family-run hotel with the Lovis restaurant and bar and the Amtsalon—a wonderful oasis and very tastefully decorated. The Chateau Royal in Berlin-Mitte—each room is individually designed with original works by renowned contemporary artists; centrally located close to Friedrichstrasse in Mitte, in an historic building, with a great bar and restaurant. And the Hotel Orania in Berlin-Kreuzberg, in the middle of the Kreuzberg Kiez, has a great bar, the ultimate Peking duck in the restaurant and the Breakfast Club. They’re known for their cultural events like concerts, literature etc. —Stefanie Hering

Chateau Royal - New and cool hotel owned by the guys behind Grill Royal, Berlin’s see-and-be-seen steakhouse. —Nina Knaudt. I have yet to find a hotel that captures Berlin the way it should. Chateau Royal is an art-filled hotel that is making a claim for that title. It’s a year old and they have a really interesting art collection. I’m planning a staycation there soon! —Eugenia Gonzalez 

Hotel de Rome is a small luxurious hotel (by Rocco Forte) in a former bank building in the heart of East Berlin, with a pool in the former vault. It has a beautiful roof terrace from which you can see the former court library, the Humboldt University, the State Opera and the TV tower, among other things. The square in front of the hotel was the site of the Nazi book burning, which is commemorated by a monument by Micha Ullman (a room with empty bookshelves in the ground). Das Stue is a relaxed hotel in the former Danish Embassy from the 1930s. Located right next to the Tiergarten Park and also adjacent to the Berlin Zoo with a private entrance. And there’s Soho House—the building was constructed in the New Objectivity style, initially as a department store for Jewish entrepreneurs. Under the Nazis it served the Hitler Youth, later in the GDR as the headquarters of the SED party. —Claudio Kühn

Telegraphenamt - This new hotel has such a central location, right in the center of the Mitte action yet somehow removed on a quiet street in a beautiful historic brick building. The food is delicious but a bit too fussily plated for my taste. What I really liked was the size and the eclectic design of the rooms. —Gisela Williams.  I like the big lobby and the historical building it’s located in and the rooms are definitely spacious. Book one with a view to the park. Location is king here. —Antje Wewer

Wilmina - I love this special only-in-Berlin location and the minimal rooms, which are nonetheless warmly designed. Plus, the Wilmina has a rooftop with a view and a pool and a very nice sauna (you’ll appreciate one, if you visit in winter). Right around the corner you’ll find the most charming Königsberger Marzipan Shop (since 1949) for a great foodie souvenir. —Antje Wewer. The location is a bit far away from all of Berlin’s action — at the far end of Kantstrasse in Charlottenburg —but the building itself is kind of magical,  like a lost castle hidden behind the facade of an old courthouse. Of course, the history of the space is not very romantic: it was at one point a women’s prison. Somehow, though, the architects Grüntuch Ernst have done a good job of exercising the bad juju yet still acknowledging its history. The restaurant Lovis, overseen by chef Sophia Rudolph, is worth a visit on its own. —Gisela Williams

The Hoxton Charlottenburg - The Hoxton is the new kid on the hotel block in Charlottenburg, right off Ku’damm. The vibe is young and uncomplicated, and the rooms are all very comfortable with an easy going English countryside twist. The lobby sports a big bar and is a good hangout, if you want to work with your laptop during the day. And as the Hoxton Group always does, they brought something new into town with them: House of Tandoor.  A contemporary Indian Restaurant and Teahouse. —Antje Wewer. I am always looking for decent Indian in Berlin and the House of Tandoor is a much welcome addition to the city’s restaurant scene. —Gisela Williams

Hotel Oderberger is resuscitation at its best! A family from Berlin turned a dormant bathhouse into a vibrant hotel. A historic house where you can both spend and swim the night away. And the small Linnen B&B is the perfect place to authentically get to know the Prenzlauer Berg district of Berlin. The guests are young, independent, and are searching for a home away from home. —Robert Kittel

FOOD, DRINK + AFTER HOURS

Coffee + Breakfast

Bonanza Coffee by Kiduk Reus has cafes all over the city for great coffee and pastries. —Meike Peters

For breakfast I always go to the Literaturhaus café in Fasanenstrasse. In good weather you can sit in the garden or on the terrace, but the winter garden and the old villa are always nice as well. —Stefanie Hering. 

Frea Bakery for coffee and lunch or Heide's, Spindler or Café Frieda for brunch. —Nina Knaudt

Daluma for vitamins and juices. —Alex Eagle

Cafe am Neuen See for Kaffee und Kuchen (the German tradition of afternoon coffee and cake), the most beautiful Biergarten, and a boat trip on the little lake. —Meike Peters

Café Frieda - a favorite, delicious and great music. —Tina Lutz

Breakfast at Two Trick Pony —Claudio Kühn

Julius Ernst has the best French Toast in town. — Meike Peters

La Maison is the best cafe in Berlin for people watching. Get a pain au chocolat, grab a seat near the canal, and take in the most stylish people in Kreuzberg. —Rachel Coleman 

The Klub Kitchen - Great lunch place in Mitte —Tina Lutz

Material - A bakery and natural wine bar recently opened by Ebrahim (baker and also owner of Kajumi) and Carlos. Go here for the city’s best banana bread, saffron bun and sourdough bread with sardines and Spanish wine to end your day. — Meike Peters

P98A - A letterpress of world-famous font designer Erik Spiekermann with a nice cafe. —Claudio Kühn

Fine Bagels by Laurel Kratochvila, for bagels, rugelach and challah buns, and for English books (Shakespeare & Sons bookstore, founded by her husband Roman), all in one place. — Meike Peters

Lunch/Dinner

I dream about the hummus from Cafe Mugrabi. Go for a weekday brunch and order the sabich hummus with a side of shakshuka. —Rachel Coleman

I would recommend David Suchy’s FREA restaurant. It is fully vegan, but ahead of its time, always packed with a good mix of people and the food is excellent. —Robert Kittel

Paris Bar is a Berlin classic. We love it and you will love it too! —Nina Knaudt. A famous institution. Classic food in an amazing setting. —Tina Lutz. 

Berlin is a great place to have a kid for many reasons, but my favorite perk is how child-friendly all the biergartens are. My favorites are Zenner, Café am Neuen See (which is also located next to the zoo), and Zollpackhof — all of which have play areas or ample running space for kids. —Rachel Coleman

Lunch at KaDeWe’s new 6th floor —Claudio Kühn

Just 2 blocks away from the Hotel Wilmina, Gal Ben Moshe at Prism cooks his Levantine cuisine at the highest level. It is incredibly delicious, definitely one of my favorites. —Stefanie Hering

November – A Japanese/German infusion restaurant, gorgeously designed in beautiful Prenzlauerberg. —Eugenia Gonzalez 

Otto - One of the city’s most respected young chefs is Vadim Otto Ursus of Otto, a tiny but acclaimed fine-dining restaurant. —Gisela Williams and Antje Wewer. Otto is known for creative yet stunningly simple produce focused dishes (his beet with labneh and brown butter is a stunner). And don’t miss his new modern German Wirtshaus (pub), Trio, with comfort food in a relaxed yet chic atmosphere in Mitte —Meike Peters

Trio- This past spring Vadim Otto Ursus, along with his two partners Eva Alken and Clemens Roesch, opened this lively modern reimagining of the “wirthaus”, the German version of a pub, located near iconic Babylon cinema. We love the Szegediner mushroom goulash with bread dumplings and anything served with “grüne Soße”, (which translates as green sauce and which is a tangy delicious pesto-like cold dressing made with seven herbs) and the laidback local crowd. —Gisela Williams and Antje Wewer. Trio is where I recommend for anyone who wants "classic German" food in a more elevated setting. Great wines, beautiful interiors, and all the classics like matjes salad, bread dumplings, and a delicious trout cooked in butter. —Rachel Coleman. Trio for delicious German cuisine. —Nina Knaudt. For German classics. —Claudio Kühn

Dining with a view over the rooftops of Berlin, in the former 40-second club is Golvet, from chef Jonas Zörner. —Stefanie Hering

Hallmann & Klee - The two women chefs at Hallmann & Klee, Sarah Hallmann and Rosa Beutelspacher, are attracting the food-loving crowd with their innovative upscale comfort dishes like fresh and semi-dried tomatoes dressed in lavender kombucha. —Gisela Williams and Antje Wewer. 

Facil in the Hotel Mandala is an oasis in the middle of the city surrounded by bamboo located in a magnificent courtyard. Great cuisine. —Stefanie Hering

Richard – Underrated, beautiful white-tablecloth restaurant on an unexpected Kreuzberg street that serves a “bistro” menu from Sunday to Thursday. The food, service and location are like none other in Berlin. —Eugenia Gonzalez 

893 Ryotei for Japanese cuisine —Nina Knaudt

Wiener Schnitzel in Einstein Unter den Linden. —Claudio Kühn

Horváth is a two star Michelin restaurant by Sebastian Frank, for creative and bold interpretation of Austrian cuisine (try his celeriac aged for 12 months in salt dough) —Meike Peters. Horváth and Tim Raue are great options. —Claudio Kühn

Eins44 in Neukölln is located in a former essence distillery. The food from Julius Nowak is contemporary, uncomplicated, seasonal and regional. —Stefanie Hering

Cookies Cream - A nice vegetarian option: you have to walk through an ugly backyard to get to this trendy restaurant. —Claudio Kühn When it comes to elevated vegan and vegetarian food, Berlin has been pushing the envelope for years. One of our favorite classic spots is Cookies Cream, a loft-like space hidden in an alley just a few blocks from Brandenburg Gate, and one of the first vegetarian restaurants in Europe to win a Michelin star. They will soon be installing a new chef which should shake up the kitchen and possibly take it to the next level. —Gisela Williams and Antje Wewer. 

For fine Berlin cuisine with excellent wines in a historic setting, go to the Rutz Zollhaus in Kreuzberg directly on the banks of the Landwehrkanal. —Stefanie Hering

Ernst - An eight-seat counter restaurant, the philosophy and techniques are grounded in Japanese cuisine with a strong focus on the sourcing of produce. It has one Michelin star. — Meike Peters. Ernst is a produce focused European omakase restaurant, inspired by Japanese techniques. It is closing its doors in 2024, although the ‘little brother’ Julius will remain open. —Claudio Kühn

Julius, the casual little 'brother’ of Ernst, Julius is a creative and casual spot for brunch, lunch, wine and dinner —Meike Peters

Nobelhart & Schmutzig by Billy Wagner and Micha Schäfer is known for creative simplicity, focussing on the seasons and the region’s bounty. It has one Michelin star and is ranked no. 45 on the World’s 50 Best. —Meike Peters. Nobelhart & Schmutzig is produce focused, in a rough and stylish atmosphere. —Claudio Kühn

Borchardt - Classic and a must for a Schnitzel lunch! —Nina Knaudt. Classic but cool with the best schnitzel in town. —Tina Lutz

Tadim – This Turkish restaurant in the heart of gritty Kottbuser Tor serves incredible takeout. Order the Lahmaçun with added Döner meat and all the fillings. You will not regret it! —Eugenia Gonzalez 

Knödelwirtschaft for German dumplings —Claudio Kühn

Another compelling trend in the city is chefs who are cooking with fire. Our favorite of the lot is Kramer, which opened at the start of this year by the ambitious restaurateur and ceramicist Fabian Kramer and is located in the bohemian cool Kreuzkölln neighborhood. It’s a stunning space filled with hanging plants and Japanese-style ceramics (made by Fabian) with a wood grill and bread oven at its center. —Gisela Williams and Antje Wewer

Bostich - French Bistro —Nina Knaudt

Barra - Portuguese restaurant in the heart of Neukölln. Must book way in advance as it is tiny, but the food never disappoints. Their fried chicken sandwich is famed throughout the city and kept its lines long during the pandemic. —Eugenia Gonzalez. 

Grill Royal - A place to see and to be seen. —Claudio Kühn. Our forever fancy classic. Also must visit! —Nina Knaudt. Trendy, fancy, expensive, great location right on the river Spree. —Tina Lutz

Lunch at Chipperfield Kantine —Claudio Kühn

Kin Dee - We love to support Berlin’s kickass women chefs; our friend Dalad Kambhu has been serving up beautiful seasonal Thai dishes family style at the intimate Kin Dee for a few years now. —Gisela Williams and Antje Wewer. Delicious thai restaurant with a Michelin star and the most beautiful female model chef. You will love it! —Nina Knaudt

Clärchens Ballhaus - A historic dance hall from 1913, now renovated, offering casual German food. —Claudio Kühn

Lila – Peruvian chef who makes the best truffle pasta and ceviche in town. The location also can’t be beat – right on Paul Linke Ufer on the canal in Kreuzberg. —Eugenia Gonzalez

Diener - Original from the 60s, very Berlin, not fancy but truly special —Nina Knaudt

Television tower restaurant - Amazing views (best at sunset) from the revolving restaurant. The interior design has not changed since the tower was opened in 1969 in East Berlin. —Tina Lutz

AVIV 030 - Typical example of one of the many restaurants opened by young Tel Avivis in recent years. —Claudio Kühn

Käfer at the Reichstag. Skip the lines by booking a table at the rooftop restaurant Käfer with an incredible view. The entrance is free. —Tina Lutz

A Pastrami sandwich at Mogg —Claudio Kühn

If you're in a group, go to Estelle in Prenzlauer Berg for dinner. The move is to order their family style sharing menu, which is a huge selection of local produce-focused dishes (the final course is always their homemade pizza, so save room!). —Rachel Coleman

Montraw Restaurant —Alex Eagle

Lode & Stijn - A casual fine dining stand out. Go there before it closes. —Claudio Kühn

Goldener Hahn – Italian Kreuzberg institution (cash only!) —Eugenia Gonzalez

Sathutu - A Sri Lankan restaurant great for spicy curries and fish, plus plenty of natural wines. Germans don't really love spicy food, so this is where I go to fill the craving! —Rachel Coleman

Everyone who visits Berlin should try our fast food Döner and Currywurst. Döner Kebap at Pamfilya and Currywurst sausage at Curry 36  —Claudio Kühn. 

Street Food/Markets

Thaipark street food on weekends in Berlin’s Preußenpark. The Konopke curry sausage has been under the U-Bahn Schönhauser Allee since 1930. The original kebab and Döner at HASIR OCAKBAŞI in the Oranienstraße has been there since 1970. —Stefanie Hering

The farmers market in Wochenmarkt Karl-August-Platz on Saturdays, for veg, cheese, bread, sausages, sauerkraut and Spreewald Gurken (gherkins), and for fantastic post-shopping crêpe (with lemon) and galettes (with Comté and egg) —Meike Peters

Markthalle Neun - The Markthalle Neun in Kreuzberg has lively and incredibly delicious street food stalls every Thursday from 5-10pm. —Stefanie Hering. Part market, part restaurants. Packed on the weekends. Perfect for food shopping and hanging out with a drink. Go to Kumpel & Keule for amazing meat. —Eugenia Gonzalez 

Saturday market on Winterfeldplatz —Claudio Kühn

Bars + Nightlife 

Wax On Bar - In the past, the pubs on Weserstraße in Neukölln only served bottled beer, now people come here for the best drinks. Tiger Bar is a trendy bar with latin influences. Freundschaft (which means friendship in German) is a great modern wine bar, also good for snacks. Motif for natural wine. —Claudio Kühn

My favorite bar in town is the Victoria Bar. Best drinks, great art and amazing people behind the bar. —Stefanie Hering. Victoria Bar is a classic for drinks and great cocktails —Nina Knaudt. A good classic American bar —Claudio Kühn. There’s very few bars where I can take my parents and my friends. You can go for an apero, you can for happy hour, or end of the night. It’s an incredible Berlin institution and the bouncers, the wait staff and bartenders are a scene unto themselves. —Eugenia Gonzalez 

Shizuku - This small sake bar is completely inconspicuous from the outside. Sake36 is a great sake bar run by techno legend Richie Hawtin. Buck & Breck has world-class drinks in a small bar with only a dozen seats at a long table and perfect service. —Claudio Kühn

Rhinoçéros by Bénédict Berna, similar to Tokyo jazz kissa, you listen to vintage Jazz records (on a vintage hi-fi sound system) while enjoying French wine and cheese, or Japanese whiskey —Meike Peters 

You can end the night in the weird Kumpelnest 3000, a legendary bar in a former brothel, where Karl Lagerfeld did a shoot with Claudia Schiffer. —Claudio Kühn

Hotel de Rome’s rooftop bar for gorgeous views, a sundowner and Neapolitan style pizza baked on the rooftop — Meike Peters

For electronic music, it is worth checking the programme at Resident Advisor. Berghain is perhaps the best and most famous techno club in the world. Located in an old bunker, it is known for its hard door and great bookings as well as for the sunrises in Panorama Bar. Other hot clubs include OST (industrial) and Kater Blau (more whimsical). If you (literally) only want to dip your feet in the water, you can grab a beer in the sun at Club der Visionäre, a light version of the Berlin techno scene right on the Spree river. —Claudio Kühn

SHOPPING

You’ll definitely find some extraordinary pieces at Andreas Murkudis at Potsdamer Straße. His concept store is located directly in the old printing house of the Tagesspiegel, the newspaper of the capital. Fiona Bennett has the most beautiful hats in town, right next door. Esther Perbandt, who is famous for her creations in black and known by "The Cut” has her store in Berlin Mitte. And don’t forget the KaDeWe, Berlin's oldest department store, still culty. For Hering Berlin's tableware, collectibles and lighting, meet me at our historical flagship villa at Berlin-Schlachtensee, directly at Mexikoplatz. —Stefanie Hering

Kadewe - Famous department store with a food department on the top floor, a great place to have lunch. —Tina Lutz

Andreas Murkudis - Berlin’s best designer fashion store, in the back of a courtyard. —Tina Lutz. The best department store in Germany, you have to go! —Nina Knaudt

Maryam Keyhani- If Salvador Dali was a milliner, he would be the lovely Maryam Keyhani. We love her joyful, surreal hats that are in the shapes of giant Meringues or dollops of whipped cream. Her headwear is all about sparking joy. We love that you can still find designers that refuse to be motivated by commercial gain here in Berlin. And her new shop! It’s not even a shop in the traditional sense of the word. She opens whenever she feels like it (or by appointment) usually during the day on Sunday, and keeps it open as long as it attracts a curious group of people, which it never fails to do. If you are not following Maryam on Instagram, sign up, her posts are always both honest and delightful. —Gisela Williams and Antje Wewer 

Suarezstraße - For vintage finds; very old school and worth a visit —Nina Knaudt

The New Black - for vintage —Alex Eagle

Marsano - A flower shop with a vintage store —Nina Knaudt

Hardt is the best for designer consignment. They get new items every week; expect lots of Acne, Jil Sander, Helmut Lang and newer brands like Aimé Leon Dore. —Rachel Coleman

The Sunday flea market at Arkonaplatz or Straße des 17. Juni —Nina Knaudt

The Store Berlin - In the ground floor of the Soho House—a great place for clothes, presents, books and food. —Tina Lutz

Amore is an Italian grocery store that also carries a gorgeous selection of Alessi kitchen gadgets, plus their in-store merch (scarves, tops, sweatshirts) is a great souvenir to bring back from Berlin. —Rachel Coleman

Modulor Berlin - The best art, stationery and handicraft store in the world! —Tina Lutz

Korbinian Ludwig Heß – Amazing shoes, both bespoke and RTW. James Whitfield, a Savile Row-trained tailor. Burg&Schild and dc4 for Japanese denim. Dussmann, a huge book and music paradise —Claudio Kühn

Hacking Gutenberg Workshop/coffee-letterpress (P98) - Workshop and letterpress studio of world-famous font designer Erik Spiekermann, including a nice cafe. —Claudio Kühn

Museums & Memorials

Be sure to see the Brandenburg Gate, Holocaust Memorial, Checkpoint Charlie & Wall Museum, the Jewish Museum, Museum Island and the Berlin Wall Memorial along Bernauer Strasse. Visit the free Memorial Museum and end up in Oderberger Str. for lunch, coffee and cake, or dinner in one of the many restaurants. —Tina Lutz

Unlike in other cities, the most important collections are divided among many houses. The Staatliche Museen Berlin with the Museumsinsel are an obvious highlight, e.g. the Bode Museum and the Neues Museum. Another favorite is the Gemäldegalerie – nowhere else is there such a high quality collection of old masters with so few visitors. —Claudio Kühn

For me, the must-see museum is the Neue Museum, impressively renovated by the architect David Chipperfield. —Stephanie Hering. Climb to the top of the dome for a great view, and visit the beautifully renovated museum by David Chipperfield, home of the famous Nofretete bust. — Tina Lutz. Just re-opened and re-constructed by Chipperfield architect, a must! —Nina Knaudt

Das Kleine Grosz Museum – An inconspicuous museum dedicated to the painter Grosz in a former petrol station (with a play on words in the name, as Grosz is pronounced like “groß“ (“big“ in German), so "small big museum"). —Claudio Kühn

KINDL – Contemporary art museum in a former brewery in Neukölln (the Bushwick of Berlin). Has a nice café in the brewhouse. —Claudio Kühn. Absolutely worth checking out! —Stephanie Hering

Neue Nationalgalerie - Perhaps the most beautiful building in the world. The plan was originally designed as a corporate building for Bacardi. The Jewish architect Mies van der Rohe returned to his homeland, which was seen as a gesture of reconciliation. At the time of the division of the city, the modern, open architecture was also a deliberate sign of the West towards GDR architecture. Very good collection and exhibitions. —Claudio Kühn. For modern and contemporary art, I love the Neue Nationalgalerie or Hamburger Bahnhof. Both are in buildings that are works of art themselves (the Nationalgalerie was designed by Mies van der Rohe, and the Bahnhof is Berlin’s former train station). —Rachel Coleman

Jüdisches Museum - Divided into an old building (Berlin's former supreme court) and a new building worth seeing by Libeskind. The focus is not only on the Third Reich, but exhibits more than 1,000 years of Jewish history in Central Europe. —Claudio Kühn

Anoha in the Jewish Museum is our favorite indoor children's play space in Berlin. The space is beautiful (think design-forward structures, not plastic Fisher-Price) and good for babies and older kids alike. —Rachel Coleman. The Jewish museum for children. Based on the story of Noah’s Ark, this museum is like nothing you have ever seen. If you travel with children you must visit here. Also, tickets should be booked online in advance!!! —Eugenia Gonzalez 

Private art collections & galleries

Sammlung Boros - This is the #1 private contemporary collection in Berlin, in an old bunker in Mitte. —Tina Lutz. 

The Boros Collection is the most widely known private art collection, but there are two lesser-known collections: the Feuerle and the Sammlung Hoffman. The Feuerle is an above-ground telecommunications bunker that was redesigned by John Pawson that has a beautiful private Chinese art collection. And the Sammlung Hoffman is the private home in the heart of Mitte, which Frau Hoffman opens every Saturday for guided tours. Both have to be booked in advance, online. —Eugenia Gonzalez 

To get the feeling of the 80s/early 90s of Berlin, you should visit House Schwarzenberg with the Cinema Central, the Escloraque Rümpschrümp and the Monstercabinet.—Stephanie Hering

The Helmut Newton Foundation - Photos by the late artist in a former dining club. —Alex Eagle

There are too many museums and galleries in Berlin to list; here are just a few favorites: Museum Hamburger Bahnhof, Berlinerische Galerie, Galerie König. —Tina Lutz

Kunstwerke Berlin – or the KW Institute for contemporary art. (Across the street is a great place for lunch, Mogg Fine Foods. And both are not far from Clärchens Ballhaus, an afternoon dance café. —Stephanie Hering

Sprüth Magers - The Berlin branch of the international gallery. Also worth checking out: Gallery Weekend. —Claudio Kuhn

At Gallery Weekends and Art Berlin, the Wilhelmhallen in Reinickendorf are musts for art lovers. —Stephanie Hering

König Galerie in St Agnes - Great gallery, great building (a brutalist church). —Claudio Kühn. In a church and super cool! —Nina Knaudt 

Stoscheck Collection for those who love video art is a must. —Stephanie Hering

Exhibitions to check out this fall

The Gropius Bau is one of our favorite museums in Berlin because it always offers an eclectic mix of exhibitions, plus it has a great bookshop and boasts one of the best canteens in town: Beba, an Israeli café on the ground floor. This fall check out the retrospective of General Idea, a radical artist collective founded in Toronto in 1969. An exhibition at Berlin’s Humboldt Forum which runs through Nov 26th asks questions like "What is a good death?" and "What will remain of us?" During the Fiesta de Día de Muertos (Nov 2-4) admission to the exhibition will be free until 10 pm. And here is a great reason to take a trip out to Potsdam, a former royal city where many of its historic buildings and parks have been awarded UNESCO World heritage status: On November 17th the excellent Barberini Museum will be opening “Edvard Munch: Trembling Earth” an exhibition which consists of over a hundred landscape paintings and drawings. Up until April next year. —Gisela Williams and Antje Wewer

Architectural Highlights

Hansaviertel – A Modernist housing estate built during the Interbau International Building Exhibition in 1957 as part of the city's post-war reconstruction. Designed as an antidote to the horrors of war and the failures of pre-war urban living conditions as well as the ‘Russian Confectionery Style’ in the East, it showcases visionary architecture, e.g. from Walter Gropius, Oscar Niemeyer, Alvar Aalto, and Arne Jacobsen. Design lovers may be interested in the horseshoe settlement Hufeisensiedlung. Or a night at the rentable museum apartment Tautes Heim ‘Horseshoe Estate'. A pioneering example of modernist urban housing built in the 1920s, it was designed by architect Bruno Taut and urban planner Martin Wagner. Its innovative design, characterized by colorful facades and garden city principles has earned it a UNESCO World Heritage designation. The Tempelhof Airport (guided tour) plus Tempelhofer Feld is another interesting site. Norman Forster called it the "mother of all airports." After its closure, the airfield was turned into a park.  —Claudio Kühn

Music

Berlin is world-famous for classical music and techno. The Berliner Philharmoniker conducted by Kirill Petrenko is one of the best orchestras in the world. They play in a post-war building with a golden tent roof and 360-degree seating which was designed to democratize the enjoyment of music and became the model for the Sydney Opera House. Akademie für Alte Musik is great for early music. Berlin is lucky to have three fantastic opera houses: Staatsoper Unter den Linden, Deutsche Oper and Komische Oper. Other recommendations include Pierre Boulez Saal, a concert building for chamber music and Piano Salon Christopheri which hosts intimate, semi-professional piano concerts in a hall used for piano restoration. For jazz, Donau 115 is a casual, young alternative to the established places such as A-Trane, B-Flat and Zig Zag.  —Claudio Kühn

OUTDOORS

Liebermann Villa am Wannsee - The former summer residence of the artist Max Liebermann, in a beautiful house and garden right at the lake (at Wannsee, you can also rent boats for 4 for sailing). —Meike Peters

Comenius Park – A beautiful quiet garden, perfect for a read. —Claudio Kühn

If you need to escape the city, my favorite place is Peacock Island—you cross over with a small ferry and explore the island on foot (and maybe meet a peacock). —Stefanie Hering

For a Swim: Schlachtensee in Berlin, Schlachtensee Heiligersee in Potsdam, or the Badeschiff in Treptow —Stefanie Hering. Berlin is surrounded by beautiful lakes, which can have an almost Scandinavian flair. You can walk around Schlachtensee and enjoy a beer in Fischerhütte biergarten afterwards. —Claudio Kühn

Overlooking the Glienicke Bridge, the place where the agents were exchanged from East to West is Babelsberg Palace Park, located directly on the Havel River. In the summer you can also jump into the water from there. —Stefanie Hering

Neukölln / Rixdorf is an old settlement of Bohemian religious refugees from the 17th-18th century within the more liberal Protestant Prussia. Then at the gates of Berlin, the village is now framed between the Turkish-influenced Karl-Marx-Strasse and the Arab-influenced Sonnenallee. —Claudio Kühn

The Cecilienhof Palace at the Heiligensee in Potsdam. Not far away is the Villa Jacob, whose park is always open on Sunday. Head a few steps further the Meierei to enjoy a freshly brewed beer. —Stefanie Hering

Vabali Spa - High-quality spa on large grounds, with many pools, saunas (clothing-free). Some of my friends visit the city from abroad, especially for this place. —Claudio Kühn

Art in the wild - There are more and more reasons to head out to the leafy green edges of Berlin and the most exciting, in our opinion, are all the great new art-related projects being planted there, from the art park at Schlossgut Schwante in Brandenburg to the thought-provoking exhibitions at the Haus am Waldsee in the suburban neighborhood of Zehlendorf. The Wehrmuehle in Biesenthal, a community-driven contemporary art museum that opened already a couple of years ago and hosts the annual Art Biesenthal exhibition is shaking it up in a traditionally conservative village in Brandenburg, located about an hour north of Berlin. —Gisela Williams and Antje Wewer

Potsdam & Schloss Sanssouci - Potsdam is the Versailles of Berlin, with historic palaces of the Prussian kings. Especially beautiful is Sanssouci by Frederick the Great, hosting a Caravaggio painting, among others. —Claudio Kühn
